  <title>
   <narrative xml:lang="EN">Indigenous and campesino organisations promote local development with a gender focus in Vitichi</narrative>
  </title>
  <description>
   <narrative xml:lang="EN">The social, economic, cultural and political life of the men and women of indigenous campesino communities in the municipality of Vitichi is not equal, nor just. There are conditions of exclusion and injustice in terms of gender which have been reproduced over time and negatively affect the rights of women. The exercising of power by men in the local organisational structures highlight the conditions of disadvantage faced by women. The most important positions are held predominantly by men and as such the needs and demands discussed and prioritised by community organizations are based on the perspective of men. The indigenous (ayllu) and campesino (union) organisations struggle to engage the attention of the municipal government and secure meaningful development for the communities in the project area. The project will tackle this disadvantageous situation in which men and women from the communities of the intervention area find themselves, by training them in the knowledge and management of legal norms related to municipal public management and also on exercising their rights of participation and social control within the framework of the application of the Comprehensive State Planning System SPIE. The project will also provide gender training (including masculinities) and provide accompaniment and support for communities in prioritising their needs and developing and presenting proposals to the municipal authorities to ensure these needs are met.</narrative>
  </description>
